title: For Sale:  Starr Arms .44cal Revolver - Civil War Army
postcontent:
Starr Arms .44 Caliber Army Double-Action Revolver
Genuine Civil War Relic (NOT a replica).  A prize for any Civil War enthusiast!

Serial Number 13327 (stamped into cylinder and frame [under hammer])
Patent Date Jan 15, 1956 (stamped into the side of the frame)
Starr Arms Co, New York (stamped into the side of the frame)

I would describe the condition as good considering its vintage.  The company name, patent date, serial number and other markings can easily be read in various locations where they are stamped into the metal.  There is some pitting on the frame above the magazine cylinder from oxidation.  The outline of the inspectors mark can be seen faintly where it was stamped into the wood handle, but the inspectors initials are no longer visible.  The wooden handle has a some scratches and dents.  The front trigger has approximately 1/4" of free travel in the released position, this is apparently due to a weak trigger return spring ... probably an easy fix for any competent gunsmith.

If you research this item you will find it selling for much higher prices on various internet sites ($1,000 and higher).  I am offering it for very good price … priced to sell.

Interested buyers can call/text telephone REDACTED.
_______________________________________________________________

Trivia - According to one website that I found while researching this item Clint Eastwood carried this sidearm in the movie “Unforgiven.”
_______________________________________________________________

I am providing several references here for your reading/viewing pleasure:

1.  http://www.gunsinternational.com/Star-Pistols.cfm?cat_id=110

2.  http://www.american-firearms.com/american-firearms/z-html/company-S/Starr%20Arms%20Company/Starr%20Arms%20Company.html

3.  http://armscollectors.com/mgs/starr_revolvers_week_2.htm

4.  http://www.nramuseum.com/the-museum/the-galleries/a-nation-asunder/case-38-arms-for-the-union-union-pistols/us-starr-arms-co-1858-double-action.aspx

Text found on reference #4:
“About 23,000 double-action Starr revolvers were manufactured in the late 1850s and early 1860s. Of these, most were purchased by the U.S. Army. Starr revolvers, in both single-and double-action models, represented over 12 percent of the sidearms issued to Union cavalry troops. Only Colt and Remington revolvers were more frequently encountered in the hands of Northern soldiers.

One of the earliest American double-action revolvers, this six-shot revolver has a six-inch round barrel rifled with six grooves. Over-all length is 11 5/8 inches, weight is two pounds 12 ounces, and the cylinder is 1 7/8 inches long. These revolvers have a steel blade front sight dovetailed into the barrel. A V-notch cut into the hammer lip serves as a rear sight. The Starr revolver is provided with a knurled screw on the right side of the frame which, when removed, allows the barrel to tip downwards on its hinged frame so that the cylinder can be removed.

Starr revolvers were invented by Eben Townsend Starr of New York City, grandson of Nathan Starr and son of Nathan Starr, Jr., famous U. S. swordmakers and riflemakers of Middletown, Connecticut. This model is marked on the right side of its frame "STARR'S PATENT JAN. 15, 1856.", and on the left side, "STARR. ARMS. Co. NEW YORK." The patent date refers to E. T. Starr's U. S. Patent 14,118 for a self-cocking percussion pepperbox. His U.S. Patent 30,843, December 4, 1860, was for his double-action revolver.

Starr firearms were made at Yonkers, Binghamton, and Morrisania, New York, from 1858 to 1867. The New York City address referred to the Starr Arms Company store and office at 267 Broadway. Starr double-action .44 caliber revolvers, with serial numbers from 1 to about 23,000, were manufactured first, and Starr single-action .44 caliber revolvers, with serial numbers from about 23,000 to about 54,000, last.”

title: For Sale:  To the idiot who doesn't understand the fiscal cliff
postcontent:
The fiscal cliff has little to do with the debt ceiling.  Basically it was a bipartisan agreement during the 2011 budget deal that the Bush tax cuts for everyone expire January 1st, 2013 and, according to the Budget Control Act of 2011, automatic budget cuts occur.  

If we don't go off the fiscal cliff (i.e. Republicans cave on Obama's absurd proposals), the debt ceiling will likely be removed as part of the deal and spending will likely stay the same or increase, thereby increasing our deficit and debt.  

If we do go off the fiscal cliff (at this point I hope we do so we can lay this whole higher-taxes-is-all-we-need mindset to rest) then the deficit will be cut in half (mind you it'd still be higher than any deficit pre-Obama but significantly less-bad as the $1 trillion plus deficits we've had the past four years).

If we go off the fiscal cliff the value of the dollar will likely INCREASE! Not decrease.  This is because our debt would be increasing slower (and we'd likely enter a recession, slowing inflation).

If we don't go off the cliff, the dollar will likely lose value at a greater rate.  

But in actuality, if was the three rounds of quantitative easing and tripling of the M1 and M2 that will be giving us the most trouble for the next decade.

Fort Knox isn't empty nor is the even bigger vault under NYC.  Gold may not have peaked yet but I wouldn't call it the best investment.  Guns are always good because they serve a purpose, but the gun buying fervor will die down after people realize there is little to no chance Obama can do anything with a Republican House and SCOTUS precedents securing the 2nd amendment.

Buy other metals (aluminum, metal fabricators and producers, tungsten, scrap companies) if you dare put your money in the stock market at all.

If you are worried about the apocalypse, buy cigarettes.

If you are confused by any or all of this then please use google, google is your friend.

I can meet within a reasonable distance. It is for sale only - no trades at this time!

The Browning BDA 380 pistol was introduced in 1980 or so as a compact and lightweight pistol for police and civilian use. The gun was manufactured in Italy under contract from FN Herstal (Belgium) and marketed as FN model 140DA (in Europe) or Browning BDA 380 (in USA). Some sources said that BDA 380 is a copy of Beretta 84, but close inspection shows some differences (i.e. Beretta 84 has frame mounted safety while BDA 380 has slide mounted safety). It was adopted by Belgian police.

The BDA 380 is a blow-back operated, double action semi automatic pistol. It has aluminum alloy frame and steel slide. Ambidextrous slide mounted safety switch disconnects the trigger from the hammer when engaged. The pistol featured low profile fixed sights and was available in either polished steel or blued finish, with wooden grip panels.
